-- ‚îÄ‚îÄ Contact.do ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Contact.do is a link-based contact tool that lets people share a single web link, such as contact.do/username, instead of publishing their real email address online. Messages sent through the link are forwarded to the owner's actual inbox while the underlying email address stays hidden from spammers and bots. It is not a scheduling or booking tool; it has operated as an email-privacy link service since 2018.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Historically freemium; now primarily a one-time lifetime fee for a custom link, with free signups no longer open to new users$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$$19 one-time for a lifetime custom contact link$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2018, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Small; appears to be a solo-founder or very small team, exact size not publicly disclosed$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Not publicly disclosed$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Contact.do Review 2026: What It Is, Pricing, Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Contact.do turns your email into a private shareable link. See how it works, pricing ($19 lifetime), features, and whether it fits your privacy needs.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Contact.do is a lightweight web service that converts a person's email address into a shareable link, such as https://contact.do/yourname, so the underlying email address never has to be published or typed anywhere in public. It is not a meeting-scheduling or appointment-booking product, despite the .do domain sometimes causing confusion with productivity-branded task tools; contact.do is specifically a contact and email-privacy intermediary. When someone visits a user's contact.do link and fills in a short message form, that message is automatically delivered to the account owner's real email inbox, while the sender never sees or learns the recipient's actual email address. The core value proposition is spam and scraping protection: because the real address is never printed on a web page, in a resume, or on a social media bio, it becomes far harder for bots, scrapers, and spam lists to harvest it. The service has been operating since 2018, and by its own published statistics has processed more than 20 million messages, with well over 180,000 contact links created and roughly 20,000 custom paid links actively in use, indicating a long-running, low-profile niche product rather than a fast-growing venture-backed startup. Contact.do's form submissions are protected by Google's reCAPTCHA to filter out automated spam before it reaches a user's inbox. Core features include a randomly generated free-style link, an optional custom or vanity link such as contact.do/yourname instead of a random string, basic click and message statistics so a user can see how their link is performing, and the ability to unlink or disable forwarding for a given email address at any time without deleting the link entirely. As of the current pricing structure, new free accounts are no longer being accepted, and the primary paid offering is a one-time lifetime fee of nineteen dollars for a custom contact link, a departure from typical subscription SaaS pricing that instead resembles a one-off handle purchase. Contact.do also runs a referral program that pays existing users ten dollars for every new paid user they refer, functioning as a low-cost customer acquisition channel for what appears to be a small, bootstrapped operation with no publicly disclosed headquarters or team size. The tool is best suited to individuals, such as freelancers, consultants, content creators, and open-source maintainers, who want a single, memorable, spam-resistant way for strangers to reach them without revealing a personal or work email address. It is less relevant for businesses needing full help-desk, CRM, or ticketing functionality, since it offers none of the conversation history, team routing, or multi-channel support features found in dedicated customer-communication platforms; it is a narrowly scoped, single-purpose contact-privacy utility rather than a full communications suite.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '18c9fbe6-5820-4126-a95d-86d665274a7d';

