-- ‚îÄ‚îÄ Container Registry Service ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$'Container Registry Service' is a generic, descriptive term for cloud-hosted or self-hosted repositories that store, version, and distribute container images, most commonly Docker or OCI-format images, so they can be pulled by orchestration platforms like Kubernetes. It is not a single branded product; the term covers offerings such as Docker Hub, Amazon Elastic Container Registry, Google Artifact Registry, Azure Container Registry, GitHub Container Registry, and self-hosted options like Harbor. This entry treats the term generically because no single vendor named exactly 'Container Registry Service' could be verified as the intended product.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Varies by provider; typically usage-based, combining storage and data-transfer or egress charges, with free tiers for public images$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Varies by provider; many offer a free tier for public repositories or small-scale use$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(NULL, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Not applicable; this is a generic service category spanning multiple vendors rather than a single company$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Not applicable; this is a generic service category spanning multiple vendors rather than a single company$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Container Registry Service Explained: Options, Pricing 2026$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$What is a container registry service? Compare Docker Hub, AWS ECR, Google Artifact Registry, Azure ACR, GHCR and Harbor on features, pricing and fit.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$'Container Registry Service' is used here as a general, descriptive label for the broad category of cloud and self-hosted services that store, version, secure, and distribute container images, most commonly images built to the Docker or OCI (Open Container Initiative) format, so they can be pulled and run by container runtimes and orchestrators such as Docker, Kubernetes, Amazon ECS, or Nomad. Because no single company markets a standalone product literally branded 'Container Registry Service,' this entry is written as an honest category overview rather than a review of one specific vendor; readers evaluating a container registry should treat the named options below as the concrete products to compare. The major public cloud providers each operate their own managed registry. Amazon Elastic Container Registry, known as ECR, is deeply integrated with AWS services like ECS, EKS, and CodePipeline, and adds features such as image vulnerability scanning, lifecycle policies for automatically expiring old images, immutable tags, and cross-region or cross-account replication. Google Artifact Registry is Google Cloud's registry, which succeeded the older Google Container Registry and extends beyond container images to also host Maven, npm, Python, and other package formats, with vulnerability scanning through Google's Container Analysis API and tight integration with GKE and Cloud Build. Azure Container Registry plays the equivalent role inside Microsoft Azure. GitHub Container Registry, known as GHCR, is bundled with GitHub Packages and is popular with teams that already build and store their code on GitHub, since it shares GitHub's permission model and integrates natively with GitHub Actions CI/CD pipelines. Docker Hub remains the largest and most widely used public registry and is often the default location container images are published to for open-source and public distribution, though its free tier enforces pull-rate limits that can affect unauthenticated or high-volume automated pulls in CI/CD systems. For organizations that need to self-host a registry rather than use a cloud vendor's managed offering, Harbor is a widely adopted open-source, CNCF-graduated registry that adds role-based access control, vulnerability scanning, image signing, and replication on top of base registry functionality, and JFrog Artifactory is a common commercial alternative that supports container images alongside many other artifact types in one universal repository manager. Across these options, common capabilities buyers should expect include private and public repository support, access control and authentication, automated vulnerability and CVE scanning of stored images, image tag immutability and retention or lifecycle policies, replication across regions for availability and latency, and integration with CI/CD tooling so a build pipeline can push new image versions automatically. Pricing models vary by vendor but are typically usage-based, combining a per-gigabyte storage charge with data-transfer or egress fees, and most providers offer a limited free tier aimed at public images, personal projects, or small teams. Choosing among these services generally comes down to which cloud or CI ecosystem an organization is already standardized on: teams running workloads on a specific public cloud typically default to that cloud's native registry for simpler identity and networking integration, teams centered on GitHub often prefer GHCR for workflow simplicity, and organizations with strict compliance, air-gapped, or multi-cloud requirements often choose a self-hosted option like Harbor or a universal artifact manager like Artifactory.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'c8b68842-72f9-4433-8892-912b315328ba';

