-- ‚îÄ‚îÄ contrib.rocks ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$contrib.rocks is a free web tool that generates a single collage-style image showing the avatars of a GitHub repository's top contributors, which maintainers can embed in their README file or website so the contributor list stays automatically up to date. It was created and is maintained by developer Suguru Inatomi, GitHub handle lacolaco, with its underlying open-source code dating to 2019. It is widely used across open-source projects as a lightweight way to publicly recognize contributors without manually maintaining a list.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free, no paid tiers$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2019, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Individual open-source maintainer project, not a company$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Not applicable; an open-source project with no registered company headquarters$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$contrib.rocks: Free GitHub Contributor Image Generator$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$contrib.rocks creates a free, auto-updating image of your GitHub repo's top contributors for your README. See how it works and how to embed it.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$contrib.rocks is a free, single-purpose web utility that generates a grid-style image of avatars representing a GitHub repository's contributors, designed specifically to be embedded in a project's README file or website. It solves a small but common open-source maintenance problem: manually listing and updating contributor names and photos in a README is tedious and quickly goes stale as a project gains new contributors, so contrib.rocks instead generates a single hosted image URL that maintainers paste into their README once, after which the image reflects the repository's current top contributors automatically whenever it is rendered, without further manual editing required. The tool was created and continues to be maintained by Suguru Inatomi, a developer who goes by the handle lacolaco on GitHub, and its underlying open-source codebase, originally published under the name contributors-img, dates to 2019, making it a long-running, community-trusted utility within the GitHub ecosystem rather than a recent or commercially backed product. Usage is intentionally simple: a user visits contrib.rocks, types a GitHub repository name in the format owner slash repository, and the tool immediately generates a preview image along with ready-to-copy HTML and Markdown embed snippets. The generated image can be customized through URL parameters, including one to control the maximum number of contributor avatars shown, defaulting to 100, one to control how many avatars appear per row in the grid, defaulting to 12, and an option to include anonymous or non-GitHub-account contributors identified only by commit email address. Clicking on any individual contributor's avatar within the embedded image links back to that person's GitHub profile, and the image as a whole can link to the repository's built-in GitHub contributors graph. Because it is entirely free with no account, subscription, or paid tier of any kind, contrib.rocks has been adopted broadly across the open-source community and is commonly seen in README files for GitHub projects ranging from small personal repositories to large, well-known open-source libraries, typically placed in a Contributors section near the bottom of the README alongside other community and license information. Its value proposition is narrow but clear: it is not a project-management tool, a CI/CD integration, or a contributor-recognition platform with badges, points, or leaderboards, unlike some more elaborate alternatives such as the All Contributors specification; it does exactly one thing, turning a GitHub repository's contributor list into a shareable, self-updating image, and does it with minimal setup. For maintainers or directory users evaluating it, the main considerations are that it depends on a small, individually maintained open-source project rather than a company with a support team or service-level agreement, and that because the image is generated dynamically from GitHub's public API each time it is requested, very large repositories with thousands of contributors may see the image take a moment to refresh or may need the maximum-contributor parameter tuned to keep the collage a manageable size. It is designed around public GitHub repositories, and its behavior with private repositories is not clearly documented in public sources.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '34f0259b-c793-4cb5-a8ec-9f6e4cd5389e';

